 experience grind mobs. For instance, against a level 50 enthralled in sirens grotto, epic will average 40dps assuming every nuke lands for 2/3. Add in magician nukes, and that mage will do upwards of 90. Compare that to the 91dps that my non-uber rogue did at level 55, and you see a disparity. Magicians are damage dealers, and little else. In order to keep up with that, we require our epic.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>There are TONS of magicians out there who don't have their epics and will NEVER get one because they're not part of the server's uber-guild,<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote><BR>Our epic doesn't require skill. It doesn't require manpower. It requires being able to tolerate weeks upon weeks of tedious killing of the same things. The only difficult part is aquiring a crown of elemental mastery from the plane of air. Our uber guilds NEVER do PoA really, and yet three dozen magicians are epic now on my server. </P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>There are warriors out there who'll never have Ntov/Sleepers gear,<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote><BR>An epic mage won't out-damage a warrior using non-uber exquisite weapons. I believe a level 60 magician will do similar damage to a warrior using epic over a medium long fight. As time increases, our DPS suffers. On uber mobs, our DPS is around 20.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>But guess what, they're STILL BALANCED with respect to other classes with similar gear<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote><BR>My non-uber rogue can out-damage a magician with basically the best gear in the game. Not by a little bit, but by a HUGE MARGIN, while being 5 levels lower to boot. The only intelligence caster class that I consider PERFECTLY balanced in respect to melees is level 60 wizards. Every other class (1-59 wizzies, 1-60 necros, 1-60 enchanters) has serious balance issues in relation to Melees. </P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>But the place where you are confused is in the epic arena. You seem to think that classes should be balanced with respect to the epic(no, not gear, because guess what - most caster gear is All/All or Enc/Wiz/Mag/Nec) that NOT EVERYONE is going to get. By this logic, instead of seeking a balance PRE-EPIC and then adding a powerful and deserved epic to every casting class, you're advocating that we have a bunch of pre-weakened classes that then we try to fix with a good "epic." <hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>"how verant-ish" remember Verant makes this game, and I have to agree that this is how things should be carried out. Epic should bring us balance in relation to epic melees, and we should also get post epic things. That is where we are lacking. An epic Magician is very well balanced compare to EPIC rogues, and EPIC warriors and EPIC paladins. It's the post-epic insane 15/19 weapons that keep Magicians (and anyone but 60 wizards) from having any semblance of balance in the end game.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>So you're basically saying that we should screw all the mages who can't get epic because hey, epics are a part of the class and mages are balanced once they get their epics? So you're saying that if a class gets a extremely powerful epic(e.g. mage, bard), they're SUPPOSED to be weak pre-epic because their epic is better than everyone else's? That logic sure seems to apply to what you're saying here, and frankly, that logic is BS.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Epic is a natural progression. To NOT include epic in class balance talks is short-sighted and doesn't fit in with how the game is played. Think about this: How much damage is a rogue with fine steel going to do. I can argue that rogues are NOT BALANCED because their damage sucks when they are using fine steel weapons. It's only through aquiring newer and better items that we improve ourselves in the game. Leaving the epic OUT OF THAT EQUATION leaves room to make an enormously overpowered class.</P><P>What is tomorrow the Magician epic was made level 60, could quad for 200, could flurry, could summon, had 50khp, had a 200 point damage shield, and fed the magician mana at the rate of 40 mana per tick. </P><P>Wouldn't that be overpowering? I use this extreme example to illustrate WHY an epic must simply be a progression in power, not a super-boost in it to otherwise unachievable levels.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>You're welcome to argue, though, but it seems that you're more interested in class envy towards the necromancer class than any sort of objective argument.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Mind pointing out my class envy? I gave a good example as to why the Necromancer epic IS NOT an uber pet. It has nothing to do with envy, it has to do with being able to see things from multiple vantages. I don't come at this thread as a Magician, I come at it as an epic Monk, epic Rogue, and pre-epic Magician. I am not saying that I am completely objective, but I do feel that my opinions are mostly fair.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>People here are crying because they don't think their epic is on par with someone else's epic but they forget to compair everything else.<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>This is exactly my point, and I will leave off with an explanation of what I mean.</P><P>An Epic weapon was not meant to be a super-powerful end-all be-all weapon. It was meant to increase the abilities you already have to a slightly higher level. In the case of the necromancer epic, I believe IT to be underpowered in relation to what necromancers get, and to what others get. I believe that were it to be a DoT that is MORE POWERFUL then the other snares they get (3000 damage maybe) it would be perfectly balanced. I do believe the effect is correct though. It saves a slot and saves a lot of mana. Verant just screwed up the numbers.</P><P>But, in that vain you must consider what you can already do. A magicians epic is borderline overpowered BECAUSE IT MUST BE. We don't get FD, or snare, or root, or stun, or mes, or harmshield, or fear or much of anything really. We get pets, nukes, malx, and mod rods. We, as a class, give up 99% of our defense in order to have superior offensive abilities. But, necromancers do not. Necromancers retain a myriad of support and defensive abilities, which is why their offensive abilities <b>must be inferior to that of a magician</b>.</P><P>I listed those BS magician abilities (of the elements) as part of that illustration. It points out exactly what we lose, in order to gain what we have.</P><P>We can all basically agree that the necromancer epic does indeed need to be tweaked. But, to give necros a pet on par with the magician epic would be unfair to magicians, and to everyone else. A class that has the best of everything is a class that is simply broken.</P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
