        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>Secondly, something I have repeated, who cares if you have high offense, low defense or *utility*. Necromancers have NO ability or spells that is raid oriented, meaning no spell or ability that makes us welcome at raids, you understand?<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Necromancers get the best mana regeneration in the game at 49th level (Lich), which gives 20 pts of mana per tick.  The best Enchanter mana regeneration (Gift of Pure Thought) caps out at 14 per tick, is a 60th level spell, just came out with Luclin, and probably drops off of a 60+ mob.  Lich is easily researchable from a word Ive gotten off 30th level mobs.</P><P>Combine Lich, or the slightly better ratio for Arch Lich (not hard to find), a Lifetap DOT and any form of Regeneration and you have a Necromancer that is the Energizer Bunny of Mana Batteries.</P><P>With all of this mana you have these options.</P><P>1. Twitch clerics who will in turn keep your melee classes alive and holding agro.<BR>2. Turn all this mana into dots to cast upon your intended victim (one of which is the Lifetap dot mentioned above).  Combined, the effect to a monster is 808 points of damage per tick, a 70% snare, a strength drop of 50 points, and an AC drop of 20  21 points.  As this approach is mana expensive and will draw agro like crazy, just split the dots up between two or three necromancers.  This allows you to fight more frequently due to less mana consumption per necromancer, allows you to recast your dots if one gets resisted, and keeps your necromancers alive due to reduced agro.<BR>3. Summon or Conjure Corpses on a failed raid.<BR>4. Summon a pet, haste it, and add more damage to the raid.</P><P>Ill be the first to admit that the strength and ac drops are not terribly significant on a raid because you are fighting creatures with insane stats, but every little bit does help.</P><P>Ok, so youre doing 808 points of damage per tick.  Each minute is 10 ticks.  On the raids that Ive seen the mini-boss fights take no less than 6 minutes (60 ticks) with some going much longer (Cazic, Tormax, etc.).</P><P>Lets say a 60 tick to kill mob is pulled to your raiding party.  You and the other necromancers unload your dots and are now doing 808 points per tick.  60 ticks later those necromancers have done 48480 points of damage, 7200 of which is healing that feeds Lich or Arch Lich.</P><P>If you pull a larger monster the same set of tactics still works.  Unload dots, send in pet, sit and med, get up and repeat when dots wear off.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>Last but not least, who told you that the vampire pet will be stronger than magician's?<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Nobody did because it isnt going to happen.  The *best* that we could hope for is that Verant chooses to use alternative models for our pets based on the level of the pet spell.</P><P>1  12 = Skeleton<BR>16  29 = Zombie<BR>34  49 = Ghoul<BR>53 = A Shadow (Like those in City of Mist), or a Shadowed Man Model (or lack thereof).  This *is* a rogue after all, make the thing invisible.<BR>56 = A Spectral Legionnaire model<BR>59 = Spectre (model doesnt need changing)</P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
