        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>1. with new mod rod clerics dont need necros to feed them (witch is a good thing really)<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>You are overlooking three important details.</P><P>First, the rod created by the new Rod of Mystical Transvergence (new mod rod spell) is lore and can generate a maximum of 660 points of mana at the expense of 900 points of health.</P><P>Second, the Cleric has 900 less points of health, and since constantly healing melee classes that are getting wailed upon generates a lot of agro, the cleric will most likely cast heal upon himself with this mana.  This will then leave less mana available for healing other members of the raid.</P><P>Third, a 47th level cleric with a wisdom score of 200 and no gear that adds mana has 1974 points of mana.  Using one of the new mod rods will just barely give back 33% of mana.</P><P>Translation?  Mod rods arent the death knell for necromancer twitching.</P><P>For reference I chose a 47th level cleric with no mana adding gear (only wisdom bonuses) because I wanted to show the mana of a minimum level cleric that is going to the planes.  True, you can go at 46th, but if you die and lose 46th while on a plane youve got some problems.  47th is a much safer minimum level.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>2. the good necro DONT stack with each other so only one necro can do any real damage<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>I believe you misunderstood what I was saying.  Im not saying that each necromancer will cast the same dots on the target.  Im saying that necromancer A casts two dots, necromancer B casts two, and necromancer C casts the remaining 3.</P><P>This strategy will work perfectly fine and is not uncommon when two necromancers are in the same group, two SKs in a group, or an SK and Nec are in a group.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>3. necros can summon coprse but i think most raids would rather have a SK cuz its rare when you need more then one coprse summond.. and when the time we do get a mass whipeout and you cant fight back.. a cleric can login his necro mule to do it<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Youve never been on a plane raid have you?  What?  Your raid group on the plane of air was a annihilated because of a bad pull?  Ever seen a wipeout against a dragon or in Chardok?</P><P>Just walking back up to your corpse isnt always wise or possible due to monsters that can see invisible players.  Sure, you can send in a rogue with hide/sneak active, but thats not always realistic and isnt the fastest of methods.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>4. due to mobs high level and pets very low level its rare when pets can do much dmg at all to a mob, now thats if the pet dont die from the first Riposte that comes its way or AE<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>I never said the pet would do tons of damage.  I said the pet would add more damage.</P><P>Concerning the single riposte that kills the pet.  Thats not very likely in nearly all raid encounters unless you are fighting a boss monster.  As one does not just roll up to a boss monster without first killing everything in your path you will already have a pet active.  Why wouldnt you send 